pull_request.body:
For rowid tables with index-based WHERE clauses, index cursors are already positioned after seek operations. Avoids inefficient IdxDelete key reconstruction by using positioned Delete instruction directly.

Closes: https://github.com/tursodatabase/turso/issues/2004

issue.title: InterPro:IPR001962 UniProtKB-KW:KW-0061
issue.body:
* **InterPro ID / label**

InterPro:IPR001962 
Molecular Function | asparagine synthase (glutamine-hydrolyzing) activity
Biological Process | asparagine biosynthetic process

UniProtKB-KW:KW-0061 human/pombe
Biological Process | asparagine biosynthetic process

* **Example sequences with problematic annotation (ID + gene/protein name):**

https://www.uniprot.org/uniprotkb/Q9NWL6/entry InterPro:IPR001962 & UniProtKB-KW:KW-0061 

https://www.pombase.org/gene/SPBC4F6.11c  UniProtKB-KW:KW-0061 

* **Description of issue**


This protein is a conserved unknown. It's in the same family as asparagine synthase, but does not appear to have asparagine synthase activity.


it contains a domain that resembles asparagine synthetases, but it lacks the key catalytic residues needed for enzymatic activity. In other words, itâ€™s structurally related to asparagine synthases but does not catalyze the conversion of aspartate to asparagine.

In a Trends in Biochemical Sciences article, Murphy & Murphy classify ASNSD1 (Asparagine Synthetase Domain Containing 1) as a pseudoenzyme within the asparagine synthetase family.
